rhus Domsogn, Hasle Herred, Århus Amt, Danmark":"Århus Domsogn, Havreballegård, Danmark",",Roskilde,Kobenhavn,Denmark":"København, København, Danmark","Denmark":"Danmark","Viborg, Denmark":"Viborg, Danmark","Roskilde, Sjælland, Denmark":"Roskilde, Sjælland, Danmark"},"nl":{"before 1264–1340":"vóór 1264–1340","1264–1340":"1264–1340","1290–Male":"1290–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1230–1270":"1230–1270","1320–Male":"1320–Overleden","1329–1368":"1329–1368","–Female":"Overleden","1230–1264":"1230–1264","11 April 1264":"11 april 1264","about 1329":"circa 1329","1368":"1368","ABT 1320":"circa 1320","before 1264":"vóór 1264","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Århus Domsogn, Hasle Herred, Århus Amt, Danmark":"Århus Domsogn, Havreballegård, Denemarken",",Roskilde,Kobenhavn,Denmark":"København, København, Denemarken","Denmark":"Denemarken","Viborg, Denmark":"Viborg, Denemarken","Roskilde, Sjælland, Denmark":"Roskilde, Sjælland, Denemarken"},"en":{"before 1264–1340":"before 1264–1340","1264–1340":"1264–1340","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1230–1270":"1230–1270","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1329–1368":"1329–1368","–Female":"Deceased","1230–1264":"1230–1264","11 April 1264":"11 April 1264","about 1329":"about 1329","1368":"1368","ABT 1320":"about 1320","before 1264":"before 1264","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Århus Domsogn, Hasle Herred, Århus Amt, Danmark":"Århus Domsogn, Havreballegård, Denmark",",Roskilde,Kobenhavn,Denmark":"Copenhagen, København, Denmark","Denmark":"Denmark","Viborg, Denmark":"Viborg, Denmark","Roskilde, Sjælland, Denmark":"Roskilde, Sjælland, Denmark","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nielsen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Niels, Jorgen, Knud, Lars, Nels, Bent, Borge, Holger, Ove, Einer, Oluf.","Danish, Norwegian, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Niels</i>, a shortened form of <i>Nikolaus</i> (see   Nicholas  ). Compare   Nielson  ,   Neilsen  ,   Nelsen  ,   Nilsen  , and   Nilson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Neilsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Ejnar, Gurli, Jorgen, Nels, Niels.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Nielsen  . Compare   Neilson   3.","Scottish (Midlothian): variant of   Neilson   1."]},{"name":"Nelsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Nels, Erik, Einer, Berger, Folmer, Holger, Iver, Juel, Morten, Thor, Uffe.","Americanized form of Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Nielsen   or   Nilsen  . Compare   Nelson  .","Flemish and German: patronymic from   Nelis  ."]}]},{"name":"Hvide","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Claus, Eberhard, Hans, Juergen, Markus, Wolfgang.","German and Jewish: variant of   Heid  .","Dutch: rare variant of <b>Van der Heide</b> (see   Vanderheide  ) and, in North America, (also) a shortened form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Heidi","meanings":["(2007: 269; 2010: NA)","German: variant (and also an Americanized form, to retain the second syllable) of   Heide  ."]},{"name":"Heider","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Otto, Fritz, Gunter, Johann, Konrad, Kurt, Matthias, Willibald.","German and Swiss German: topographic name for a heath dweller, a variant of   Heide   + the <i>-er</i> suffix denoting an inhabitant; or a habitational name for someone from any of various places called Heide or Heidau (named with the same term); the placename is common in Silesia, Saxony, and Bohemia."]},{"name":"Heid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Eckhart, Gerd, Gotthilf, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Kurt, Manfred, Ralf, Uli.","German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name from Middle High German <i>heide</i>, German <i>Heide</i> ‘heath, moor, open, uncultivated land’. Compare   Heath  .","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Haido</i>, a short form of any of various compound names beginning with <i>haid</i> ‘heath’ (i.e. wasteland, often with heather)."]},{"name":"Heyde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Achim, Dietrich, Helmut, Volker.","German: topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, unprotected, open country, a variant of   Heide  ."]},{"name":"Hiday","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Heide  ."]}]},{"name":"Galt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gall  , with excrescent <i>-t</i>.","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>galte</i>, <i>gaute</i>, <i>gault</i> ‘boar, hog’ (Old Norse <i>gǫltr</i>, <i>galte</i>), denoting someone thought to resemble the animal in appearance or character."],"variants":[{"name":"Gault","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire), Irish (Antrim and Derry), and English: variant of   Galt  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Waldo</i>, from <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’.","French: habitational name from any of the places called Le Gault (for example in Loir-et-Cher and Eure-et-Loir), named with ancient Germanic <i>walthu-</i> ‘wood, forest’. Compare   Legault  ."]},{"name":"Gaut","meanings":["English: variant of   Galt  .","In some cases possibly also French: variant of   Gault  ."]},{"name":"Gall","meanings":["Scottish, Welsh, and Irish: nickname from Celtic <i>gall</i> ‘foreigner, stranger’, a word found in Irish, Gaelic, and Breton. In the Scottish Highlands the Gaelic term <i>gall</i> was applied to people from the English-speaking lowlands and to Scandinavians; in Ireland the same term was applied to settlers who arrived from Wales and England in the wake of the Anglo-Norman invasion of the 12th century. This surname is also found at an early date in Lincolnshire, where it apparently has a Breton origin (compare 4 below and   Legall  ), having been introduced by Breton followers of the Norman Conquerors.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Gale  .","French, German, Danish, Polish, and Czech; Slovak (mainly <b>Gáll</b>); Hungarian (<b>Gáll</b>): from the Latin personal name <i>Gallus</i>, originally a Roman surname meaning ‘Gaul’ or ‘rooster’ (see   Gallo   2). The name was widespread in Europe during the Middle Ages, in central Europe largelly due to the cult of a 7th-century Irish monk and missionary, Saint Gall, whose name, Latinized as <i>Gallus</i>, is presumably of Celtic origin (see 1 above). Among other things, Saint Gall established a Christian settlement to the south of Lake Constance, which became the monastery later known as St. Gallen. The Latin(ized) name <i>Gallus</i> was taken into Czech as   Havel  , into Polish as <i>Gaweł</i> (see   Gawel  ), into Slovak and Hungarian as <i>Gál</i> (see   Gal  ), and into Slovenian and Croatian as   Gal  ."]},{"name":"Gatt","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire): variant of   Galt  . An alternative derivation from Older Scots <i>gate</i>, <i>gait</i>, <i>gaet</i>, <i>get(t)</i> (Old Norse <i>gata</i>) ‘way, road, path; street’ (see   Gates  ) is theoretically possible, but there is no evidence to link this to any of the historical bearers of the name in the British Isles.","South German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed from the same root as the Middle High German word <i>gate</i> ‘companion, compatible person’."]}]},{"name":"Ebbe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["short form of various names formed with <i>eber</i> ‘boar’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ebbe Nielsen Hvide Galt was born before 1264, in Denmark as the son of Niels Jurissen Hvide Galen. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Ingerd Margrete Nielsen Hvide Galt. He died in 1340, in his hometown."},"et":{"before 1264–1340":"enne 1264–1340","1264–1340":"1264–1340","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1230–1270":"1230–1270","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1329–1368":"1329–1368","–Female":"Surnud","1230–1264":"1230–1264","11 April 1264":"11. aprill 1264","about 1329":"umbes 1329","1368":"1368","ABT 1320":"umbes 1320","before 1264":"enne 1264","1320":"1320","1264":"1264","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Århus Domsogn, Hasle Herred, Århus Amt, Danmark":"Århus Domsogn, Havreballegård, Taani",",Roskilde,Kobenhavn,Denmark":"København, København, Taani","Denmark":"Taani","Viborg, Denmark":"Viborg, Taani","Roskilde, Sjælland, Denmark":"Roskilde, Sjælland, Taani"},"fi":{"before 1264–1340":"ennen vuotta 1264–1340","1264–1340":"1